<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-342-234  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 342 234.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  June 12 1989 v6 n23 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>No challenge in sight for big 3 carriers. (ATandamp;T, MCICommunications Corp, US Sprint Communications Corp market share)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brown, Bob; Runnoe, Gail.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ATandamp;T, MCI Communications Corp, and US Sprint Communications Cohold a 92 percent share of the US long-distance market.andO;Encroachment of a fourth major player does not seem likely.andP;  Thecost of offering services comparable to or exceeding the threeleaders is beyond other carriers, even the stronger companiesresulting from recent mergers and acquisitions, most analysts say.andO;The three leaders have made major investment in equipment andoffer competitive prices.andP;  Such services as WATS, fractional T-1,and 800-number options are expected of national carriers.andP;  Aminority believe a fourth competitor could emerge from a coalitionof regional carriers.andP;  Market research figures from ComputerIntelligence indicate that ATandamp;T holds a 68 percent market share,MCI 14 percent, US Sprint 10 percent, Telecom USA two percent,Allnet Communication Services one percent and the remaining 600companies five percent of the US long-distance market.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Market AnalysisTelecommunicationsMarket ShareCompetitionTelephone Companies.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   U.S. long-distance market. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>